"brand-kb/06-faq/faq-master.md": "---\ntitle: FAQ Master — Steven's Answers and Standard HVAC Questions\ncategory: faq\nthemes: [faq, integrity, fair-pricing, answer-the-phone, credentials, services]\nsurfaces: [faq, homepage, about, service-pages, blog-seed]\nquote: \"I just want them to feel taken care of.\"\nsensitivity: greenlit\nlength_words: ~830\nstatus: needs-info\nlast_updated: 2026-05-20\n---\n\n## When I call ECS, who picks up?\n\nSteven does. If he's heads-down on a job, Angel does. If they both miss it, the call goes to voicemail and Steven calls back the same day, usually inside the hour. If he's driving when you call, he'll tell you he's pulling over somewhere safe and then he'll take down your information from there.\n\n## What should I expect when a tech shows up at my door?\n\nIn uniform, clean, in a clean truck. No surprises. The truck in the driveway matches the shirt the tech is wearing matches the name on the invoice. Steven's rule for himself and anybody he ever puts on the road is that the homeowner should feel comfortable before a single word gets said.\n\n## What's your service area?\n\nThe Upstate of South Carolina. Pickens, Easley, Greer, Seneca, Sunset, and the Lake Keowee area are all in normal range. Greenville proper, Anderson, and Clemson are regular service areas too. Lake Jocassee is too far. If you're not sure whether your address is in range, call and ask.\n\n## Are you licensed and insured?\n\nYes. Steven holds the South Carolina contractor's license personally and drove to Columbia himself to pick it up. ECS is bonded and insured. Most of the techs you see out there in the Upstate aren't personally licensed because South Carolina only requires one license holder per company. Steven is the license holder at ECS, and Steven is the one showing up at your house.\n\n## What brands do you work with?\n\nSteven works on every major residential brand. For installs, ECS partners with the equipment lines that hold up best in Upstate conditions and back their warranties properly.\n\n`[NEEDS-INFO: ask Steven for preferred install brands and any brand-specific service exclusions.]`\n\n## Do you offer maintenance plans?\n\nYes. The maintenance agreement covers seasonal tune-ups and gets the customer priority scheduling. The first big maintenance agreement Steven sold at ECS was a 10-system home on Lake Keowee, and it's grown into one of his most consistent relationships.\n\n`[NEEDS-INFO: ask Steven for exact pricing tiers, what's included per visit, and frequency for residential vs. multi-system homes.]`\n\n## Do you install generators?\n\nECS is a certified Generac dealer for service and installation, but new generator installs in South Carolina require a separate plumbing license and a separate electrical license to run gas and power from scratch. Steven holds the HVAC license. For a brand-new generator install, he brings in his brother-in-law (master electrician) and the customer pulls the permits. For service, warranty work, and replacements where the gas and electrical infrastructure is already there, ECS handles it directly.\n\n## Do you do commercial work?\n\n`[NEEDS-INFO: ask Steven. Most of his current work is residential, with one restaurant rooftop reference (the Easter Sunday job). Confirm whether commercial is a published service line or referral-only.]`\n\n## Do you do duct cleaning?\n\n`[NEEDS-INFO: ask Steven. Duct cleaning is often an upsell at the big shops. Confirm whether ECS offers it, refers it out, or skips it.]`\n\n## What's your warranty?\n\nECS stands behind the work. Manufacturer warranties on equipment run per the manufacturer's terms (typically 10 years on parts for major brands with registration). ECS warranties the labor for a defined period after the install.\n\n`[NEEDS-INFO: ask Steven for exact labor warranty period, parts warranty terms by brand, and any extended warranty options offered at install.]`\n\n## How much is a service call?\n\nECS charges a fair diagnostic fee that covers the trip, the time on site, and a complete diagnosis of what's wrong with your system. The fee gets credited toward the repair if you choose to move forward.\n\n`[NEEDS-INFO: ask Steven for the exact diagnostic fee number, current as of 2026.]`\n\n## Do you offer financing?\n\n`[NEEDS-INFO: ask Steven whether ECS has a financing partner set up yet. The intake document should confirm Synchrony, Wells Fargo, GreenSky, or any preferred lender, plus terms (promotional 0% windows, typical APR).]`\n\n## Will you try to sell me a new system?\n\nNo. If your unit can be repaired, ECS repairs it. If it can't be repaired honestly, you'll get told that plainly and the conversation about replacement will be straight numbers, no urgency, no fear talk. Steven has driven an hour out of his area to look at a unit two other companies said needed a TXV and a compressor. The actual problem was a dirty filter. He cleaned the filter and went home. That's how ECS handles diagnosis.\n\n## What's the goal here? What does Steven want his name to mean to a homeowner five years from now?\n\n> \"I just want them to feel taken care of. I want the quality to be there. I just want them to not have to worry.\"\n\nThree things. You called the right person. The work was done right. You don't have to think about your HVAC system again until the next maintenance visit. That's the whole company.\n",
